                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-15T10:24:24.611-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="A common denominator"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:00:15.064-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Brett Dabruzzo’s first migraine hit when she was in high school. Pounding headaches and overwhelming nausea weren’t diagnosed as migraine until almost a decade later when Dabruzzo, Pharm.D., director, medical affairs, AbbVie, began working for a pharmaceutical company in its neurology department. A week into her job as a medical science liaison in Parkinson’s disease, epilepsy and migraine, she recognized the signs of migraine and sought help, receiving a diagnosis for the neurological disease shortly after.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Dabruzzo says she tries not to let migraine stop her – but there are times where she can’t fight it off. Missed kids’ hockey games and date nights often add up to disappointment and guilt.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“I feel like I would be a better mom if I didn't have migraine,” Dabruzzo says. “I feel like I would be a better wife if I didn't have migraine.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Like Dabruzzo, Michael Gold, M.D., vice president, neuroscience development, AbbVie, is familiar with migraine. But while he doesn’t face migraine himself, Gold watches his wife and adult children battle debilitating attacks.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <image
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:06:12.710-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:15:37.593-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Despite living with migraine, Michael Gold’s family – which includes his wife, Fanny, and children, Alexander and Ariel – loves to travel. In 2019, they and Gold explored Bryce Canyon National Park."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="The math of migraine"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/the-math-of-migraine/The Math of Migranie.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <text
                                cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:16:36.075-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:18:24.060-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                text="&lt;p>&lt;i>Despite living with migraine, Michael Gold’s family – which includes his wife, Fanny, and children, Alexander and Ariel – loves to travel. In 2019, they and Gold explored Bryce Canyon National Par&lt;span class=&quot;body-unica-14-reg&quot;>&lt;/span>k.&lt;/i>&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                textIsRich="true"/>
                            <separator_copy_copy_
                                cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:18:50.677-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:18:50.677-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:19:40.218-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:21:49.681-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>As a neurologist, Gold says he understands the mechanics of migraine – but it doesn’t make it any less difficult to see his family, who has experienced migraine for four generations, struggle.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“We’ve&amp;nbsp;seen it; we live it,” Gold says. “It’s humbling.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Based on his clinical and personal experience, Gold has seen the long journey people with migraine trek from symptom onset to accurate diagnosis and developing an appropriate treatment plan for them. He says delays in finding a tailored therapy can be spurred in part by lack of open discussion about symptoms.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:22:05.265-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-15T14:55:39.946-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Making a difference"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_1123155212
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-02T18:22:57.142-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-02T18:23:07.942-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Gold believes there’s an opportunity to improve migraine care, but it’ll take teamwork from patients, researchers and healthcare providers.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Patients, he says, can try to observe how early stages of migraine manifest and potentially avoid triggers or intervene earlier with a plan geared toward prevention in addition to acute therapy. It’s important that they share not only their symptoms with their healthcare providers but also ask questions. Researchers must continue to investigate alternative treatment avenues. Clinicians should familiarize themselves with migraine symptoms to become more comfortable addressing them.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
